body:
## Steps to Reproduce

1. Start IDEA with the M18 RC plugin installed
1. File > New Project, select Plugin type, and Next
1. After IDEA has initialised, right-click the root node in the project view and select Flutter > Open in xCode

Actual result: xCode starts, but the plugin code isn't available

Expected result: xCode opens, the plugincode is available for running, and the Run button starts the plugin example app as per:
https://flutter.io/developing-packages/#step-2c-add-ios-platform-code-hmswift

comment_data.body: I think it's opening `./plugin-name/Runner.xcodeproj`? It should be opening `./plugin-name/example/ios/Runner.xcworkspace`.
Confirmed after feedback from @stevemessick that this works if you do a Run in IDEA prior to opening in xCode. Removing M18 blocking status.

AI: Figure out a good UX to ensure a build is done prior to launching the other IDE. You may need to do a build prior to every launch, but that is time-consuming and it would be nice to not have to do it unless needed.
@mit-mit: #1527 updates our logic to open `Runner.xcworkspace`.  I believe this should be fixed?

No, it still fails if you open xCode prior to doing a built in IJ:

```
/Users/mit/tmp/untitled4/example/ios/Runner/GeneratedPluginRegistrant.m:6:9: 'untitled4/Untitled4Plugin.h' file not found
```

I think the best solution might be to do a build in IJ as part of project creation?

Ah, OK.  I like the idea of volunteering to run a build before opening.

What's the best resource to look for as a sentinel?

/cc @cbracken
@cbracken, @szakarias  : could you advise on a sentinel resource to look for to indicate that an xcode build should (not) be performed?

The ideal would be to always perform the build but Flutter should be smart enough to turn that into a no-op if everything that needs building is already built. I suspect that that's not yet feasible though it seems like something we should open a bug for.

In the meantime, the presence of a `build/ios` directory might be a sort-of dodgy heuristic that an iOS build has been done (or at least attempted) at least once. It might be ages out-of-date, but if this is specific to newly-created projects, it's probably sufficient. I'd certainly put a big TODO on that code though :)
